{
  "texts": [
    "The optimization can be subject to local constraints:0 ≤ P load i (t) ≤ P load,max i, (13) 0 ≤ P gen i (t) ≤ P gen,max i, (14) 0 ≤ S i (t) ≤ S max i,(15)where S i (t) is the state of charge of the local battery.",
    "More sophisticated versions include forecast-based optimization using Model Predictive Control (MPC), where each agent solves:min Pi(t:t+N) t+N k=t [c i (P i (k)) -λ(k)P i (k)],(16)for a prediction horizon N. This supports dynamic decision-making under uncertainty in demand or PV output.",
    "2) Non-Cooperative GameIn environments where multiple prosumers act simultaneously and selfishly, their actions impact each other through shared variables like voltage, frequency, or market prices.",
    "This leads to a non-cooperative game setup:max Ai U i (A i, A -i), ∀i ∈ N,(17)where:• U i (•): Utility function of agent i.• A i: Strategy of agent i.• A -i: Strategies of all other agents (j ̸ = i).• N: Set of all participating agents or prosumers.A classical solution concept is the Nash Equilibrium, where no agent can unilaterally improve its utility:U i (A * i, A * -i) ≥ U i (A i, A * -i), ∀A i ∈ A i, ∀i.Utility functions U i can incorporate:• Energy profit: λ(t)P i (t),• Battery wear cost: β • DoD i (t),• Comfort or preference: deviation from desired HVAC or EV charging profile, • Peer-to-peer (P2P) trade benefits or penalties.",
    "The existence of a Nash equilibrium is guaranteed under certain conditions such as convexity of utility functions and compactness of strategy sets."
  ]
}